<raw><![CDATA[    Investing.com â€“ House prices in Britain fell unexpectedly in May, data showed on Thursday.In a report, the Halifax Bank of Scotland said house prices fell 0.6% in May, after declining 0.5% in April, whose figure was revised up from 0.4%.Analysts had expected an advance of 0.6% in May.Commenting on the report, Martin Ellis, housing economist said "The mixed pattern of monthly price rises and falls so far this year is consistent with a slowing market and is in line with our view that house prices will be flat during 2010 as a whole".He added "Further falls in the number of people in employment are curbing housing demand whilst the pickup in market conditions last year has encouraged more homeowners to attempt to sell their property".Following the release of the data the pound was down against the U.S. dollar, with GBP/USD shedding 0.19% to hit 1.516.             ]]></raw>
